Last Friday, as Washington Post C.E.O. Will Lewis announced the paper=E2=80=
=99s controversial decision to forgo a presidential endorsement in the wani=
ng days before the election, the paper=E2=80=99s proprietor, Jeff Bezos, wa=
s in Switzerland with his fianc=C3=A9e and friends of the haut monde, embar=
king on a multiday, Orient Express-style rail tour from Geneva to Amsterdam=
 in celebration of Katy Perry=E2=80=99s 40th birthday. While Bezos & Co. sp=
ent the weekend celebrating the pop star, drinking Mo=C3=ABt and donning th=
ematic attire for each event, the Post ignited into yet another open revolt=
=2E

Whether or not any voter would be persuaded by the editorial board=E2=80=99=
s inevitable endorsement of Harris, Washington is a town bound by tradition=
s and pastimes, and few institutions are more hewed to this
tradition than the Post, which identifies itself more so with Bradlee, Baro=
n, Woodward, and Bernstein than its multi-centibillionaire owner. The Post=
=E2=80=99s decision to spike the endorsement not only broke with 50 years o=
f tradition, but it came during the fraught final days of the race. And it =
also forced Lewis, possibly the least popular person in town this side of D=
an Snyder, to once again foist an unpopular decision upon his reluctant cha=
rges=E2=80=94many of whom seem frightened by the state of their industry, a=
nd the majority of whom appear perennially pissed at their owner and publis=
her.

Perhaps unsurprisingly, given the characters involved, several members of t=
he editorial board resigned in protest of the non-endorsement decision. Pos=
t luminaries (including the aforementioned Baron, Woodward, and Bernstein) =
condemned it, and alarmingly, according to NPR and the Post=E2=80=99s own r=
eporting, around 10 percent
of the Post=E2=80=99s 2.5 million readers canceled their subscriptions. The=
 Post=E2=80=99s management team won=E2=80=99t confirm that number, and its =
interim-ish executive editor, Matt Murray, won=E2=80=99t even disclose it t=
o his own staff. Of course, there=E2=80=99s some nuance to calculating canc=
ellation at a subscriber business=E2=80=94with trial subscribers and expiri=
ng credit cards, etcetera=E2=80=94and a Post spokesperson notably declined =
to comment in the paper=E2=80=99s own piece about its mass churn event.

Regardless, it=E2=80=99s an inarguably substantial hit to a paper already b=
eset by years of subscriber drift, revenue losses, depleted morale, and the=
 lack of a reliable long-term strategic plan=E2=80=94not to mention a still=
 nebulous restructuring and an ostensibly vacant top editorship that no one=
 seems to covet. (Visions of the third newsroom become blurrier each day=E2=
=80=A6) Presumably, these hiccups emerged during the Perry birthday tour.

This summer, when
the Post was engulfed in the scandal over Sally Buzbee=E2=80=99s defenestra=
tion and Lewis=E2=80=99s own ethics credentials, Bezos sent a polite my-way=
-or-the-highway note from his $500 million superyacht, Koru, in the Greek I=
sles. (Koru cost twice what he paid for the Post.) On Monday, he published =
a longer, more thoughtful mini-essay in the Post explaining that his decisi=
on was motivated not by any sort of Trump obsequiousness but rather a genui=
ne desire to restore trust in a failing industry. =E2=80=9COur profession i=
s now the least trusted of all,=E2=80=9D Bezos wrote. =E2=80=9CSomething we=
 are doing is clearly not working.=E2=80=9D Indeed, it was his version of L=
ewis=E2=80=99s infamous dictate from the summer that he simply couldn=E2=80=
=99t sugarcoat it any longer: Audiences were no longer reading his colleagu=
es=E2=80=99 stuff.

=E2=80=9CNever Seen Anything Like This=E2=80=9D

Unsurprisingly, Bezos=E2=80=99s note did little to quell the frustrations i=
nside the Post, which have been playing out in contentious meetings on both=
 the news and opinion sides of the newsroom for days. Up until Wednesday, P=
ost sources were describing feelings of anger, sadness, and confusion. =E2=
=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve actually never seen anything like this,=E2=80=9D said on=
e. So it seems Bezos=E2=80=99s editorial also did little to disabuse critic=
s of their unfounded suspicion that he had preemptively capitulated to Trum=
p in anticipation of his return to the White House. Post subscribers are st=
ill expressing their frustration and, on Wednesday, Baron tweeted a link to=
 an essay encouraging Bezos to donate the paper to charity. (Great idea, Ma=
rty=E2=80=A6)

What actually accounts for Bezos=E2=80=99s decision, and its mismanaged imp=
lementation? The
right answer is almost certainly the most obvious one. During the first Tru=
mp administration, the Post thrived as a pillar of the resistance and grew =
subscriptions by 50 percent year over year. But in the years since, it has =
suffered severely, losing nearly half its audience and as much as $100 mill=
ion in annual revenue. Meanwhile, Bezos has spent years quietly and sometim=
es overtly signaling a desire to turn the Post into an at least semi-nonpar=
tisan news organization that services all Americans, rather than a regional=
 edition of the Times political report servicing anxious liberals. Apparent=
ly, Bezos understands that Republicans buy papers, too, and that advertiser=
s also want to reach them. The Post may be an institution in town, but it=
=E2=80=99s also a business.

Now, despite owning the paper, there=E2=80=99s only so much Bezos can actua=
lly do to manifest his vision for the Post=E2=80=99s editorial posture
without actually putting his hands in the dough. The most obvious lever is =
leadership. In 2022, Bezos hired David Shipley from centrist and billionair=
e-owned Bloomberg to oversee the editorial department, a move he hoped woul=
d bring a greater diversity of perspective to its opinion pages. Last year,=
 he hired Lewis, a former Murdoch deputy and onetime Dow Jones C.E.O., to r=
un the business and prioritize profitability over Pulitzers (notably, Lewis=
 was in a bake-off with another Bloomberg-world veteran, Josh Steiner). In =
both instances, Bezos hoped to burnish the Post=E2=80=99s reputation for st=
rong journalism while also moving the paper away from its reputation as a l=
iberal bulwark. Obviously, that has proven harder than he might have hoped.

Anyway, Bezos seems to have found another outlet for his frustrations in th=
e endorsement decision. Indeed, if you=E2=80=99re aspiring to create a nonp=
artisan newspaper=E2=80=94and you=E2=80=99re a little displeased
with how that=E2=80=99s been going=E2=80=94it doesn=E2=80=99t really make s=
ense to compound reputational problems by once again telling people to vote=
 for the Democratic presidential candidate, which is exactly what the Post =
has done since it began regularly endorsing candidates in 1976. Sure, even =
Bezos acknowledged that such a decision could and should have been made ear=
lier, before the final stretch of this fraught and emotionally charged camp=
aign, but such are the perils of being a titanic entrepreneur and business =
magnate with so many irons in the fire, and so many private European rail p=
arties to attend.

Not surprisingly, the vast majority of the Post=E2=80=99s own editorial boa=
rd doesn=E2=80=99t see it that way, and has said as much publicly. In a mee=
ting this week, audio of which was obtained by The Washington Free Beacon, =
Shipley told his staff that he =E2=80=9Cmade very strenuous efforts, includ=
ing a phone call [with Bezos] to change his mind, but failed.=E2=80=9D
Shipley=E2=80=99s decision to create some daylight between himself and both=
 Bezos and Lewis, who also wrote a mini-essay defending the non-endorsement=
 decision, was either bold, dastardly, defensive, or a manifestation of nak=
ed survival instincts. Never the most popular guy in the building, Shipley =
seemingly recognized that=E2=80=94in the short term, at least=E2=80=94the e=
leventh-hour non-endorsement decision was going to deliver a far more sever=
e reputational hit than one more cycle in which the never-Trumpers took sol=
ace in knowing the Post was firmly on their side. He also probably didn=E2=
=80=99t want underlings to plot a coup against him, though Lewis couldn=E2=
=80=99t be pleased that he broke rank.

In any event, there are at least two points that the critics of Bezos=E2=80=
=99s decision may not fully appreciate. First, despite their worst fears, t=
here is no evidence or indication that Bezos intends to tamper with the jou=
rnalism itself. Any sober review of the Post=E2=80=99s reporting
in recent days, weeks, or months would find zero deviation from its long-st=
anding effort to hold Trump to account. (Of course, great reporting has the=
 potential to have far greater impact on a presidential election than any e=
ndorsement, which has exactly no bearing, but whatever.) The notion that Be=
zos intends to shy away from tough journalism to placate Trump is inconsist=
ent with all the available evidence going back for nearly a decade.

Second, while this whole thing was grossly mismanaged, and has only compoun=
ded the newsroom=E2=80=99s preexisting obsession with finding its leadershi=
p guilty of philosophical adultery, it=E2=80=99s worth keeping in mind that=
 the leaders have their own misgivings about the newsroom, too. Ultimately,=
 Bezos wants to own, and Lewis wants to manage, a paper staffed by a team t=
hat supports their vision for semi-nonpartisan, future-proofed profitabilit=
y. And while they certainly don=E2=80=99t want, and didn=E2=80=99t anticipa=
te,
such a severe exodus of subscribers, they=E2=80=99re probably not terribly =
bothered by the departure of morally righteous journalists who pine for a r=
eturn to the =E2=80=9CDemocracy Dies in Darkness=E2=80=9D era, no matter wh=
at Marty posts on Twitter. As is the case in any business transformation, t=
hey may even welcome the turnover.

