          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Last Friday, as <i>=
Washington Post</i> C.E.O. <b>Will Lewis </b>announced the paper=E2=80=99s =
controversial decision to forgo a presidential endorsement in the waning da=
ys before the election, the paper=E2=80=99s proprietor, <b>Jeff Bezos</b>, =
was in Switzerland with his fianc=C3=A9e and friends of the <i>haut</i> <i>=
monde</i>, embarking on a multiday, Orient Express-style rail tour from Gen=
eva to Amsterdam in celebration of <b>Katy Perry</b>=E2=80=99s 40th birthda=
y. While Bezos &amp; Co. spent the weekend celebrating the pop star, drinki=
ng Mo=C3=ABt and donning thematic attire for each event, the <i>Post </i>ig=
nited into yet another open revolt. <br/><br/>Whether or not any voter woul=
d be persuaded by the editorial board=E2=80=99s inevitable endorsement of <=
b>Harris</b>, Washington is a town bound by traditions and pastimes, and fe=
w institutions are more hewed to <i>this</i>
tradition than the <i>Post</i>, which identifies itself more so with <b>Bra=
dlee</b>, <b>Baron</b>, <b>Woodward</b>, and<b> Bernstein </b>than its mult=
i-centibillionaire owner. The <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s decision to spike the e=
ndorsement not only broke with 50 years of tradition, but it came during th=
e fraught final days of the race. And it also forced Lewis, possibly the le=
ast popular person in town this side of <b>Dan Snyder</b>, to once again fo=
ist an unpopular decision upon his reluctant charges=E2=80=94many of whom s=
eem frightened by the state of their industry, and the majority of whom app=
ear perennially pissed at their owner and publisher.<br/><br/>Perhaps unsur=
prisingly, given the characters involved, several members of the editorial =
board resigned in protest of the non-endorsement decision. <i>Post </i>lumi=
naries (including the aforementioned Baron, Woodward, and Bernstein) condem=
ned it, and alarmingly, according to NPR and the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s own =
reporting, around <i>10 percent
</i>of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s 2.5 million readers canceled their subscri=
ptions. The <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s management team won=E2=80=99t confirm tha=
t number, and its interim-ish executive editor, <b>Matt Murray</b>, won=E2=
=80=99t even disclose it to his own staff. Of course, there=E2=80=99s <i>so=
me</i> nuance to calculating cancellation at a subscriber business=E2=80=94=
with trial subscribers and expiring credit cards, etcetera=E2=80=94and a <i=
>Post </i>spokesperson notably declined to comment in the paper=E2=80=99s o=
wn piece about its mass churn event. <br/><br/>Regardless, it=E2=80=99s an =
inarguably substantial hit to a paper already beset by years of subscriber =
drift, revenue losses, depleted morale, and the lack of a reliable long-ter=
m strategic plan=E2=80=94not to mention a still nebulous restructuring and =
an ostensibly vacant top editorship that no one seems to covet. (Visions of=
 the <i>third newsroom </i>become blurrier each day=E2=80=A6) Presumably, t=
hese hiccups emerged during the Perry birthday tour. <br/><br/>This summer,=
 when
the <i>Post </i>was engulfed in the scandal over <b>Sally Buzbee</b>=E2=80=
=99s defenestration and Lewis=E2=80=99s own ethics credentials, Bezos sent =
a polite my-way-or-the-highway note from his $500 million superyacht, <i>Ko=
ru</i>, in the Greek Isles. (<i>Koru</i> cost twice what he paid for the <i=
>Post</i>.) On Monday, he published a longer, more thoughtful mini-essay in=
 the <i>Post</i> explaining that his decision was motivated not by any sort=
 of <b>Trump </b>obsequiousness but rather a genuine desire to restore trus=
t in a failing industry. =E2=80=9COur profession is now the least trusted o=
f all,=E2=80=9D Bezos wrote. =E2=80=9CSomething we are doing is clearly not=
 working.=E2=80=9D Indeed, it was his version of Lewis=E2=80=99s infamous d=
ictate from the summer that he simply couldn=E2=80=99t <i>sugarcoat it </i>=
any longer: Audiences were no longer reading his colleagues=E2=80=99 <i>stu=
ff.</i><br/></td>
