          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Unsurprisingly, Bez=
os=E2=80=99s note did little to quell the frustrations inside the <i>Post</=
i>, which have been playing out in contentious meetings on both the news an=
d opinion sides of the newsroom for days. Up until Wednesday, <i>Post </i>s=
ources were describing feelings of anger, sadness, and confusion. =E2=80=9C=
I=E2=80=99ve actually never seen anything like this,=E2=80=9D said one. So =
it seems Bezos=E2=80=99s editorial also did little to disabuse critics of t=
heir unfounded suspicion that he had preemptively capitulated to Trump in a=
nticipation of his return to the White House. <i>Post </i>subscribers are s=
till expressing their frustration and, on Wednesday, Baron tweeted a link t=
o an essay encouraging Bezos to donate the paper to charity. (<i>Great idea=
</i>, Marty=E2=80=A6)<br/><br/>What <i>actually </i>accounts for Bezos=E2=
=80=99s decision, and its mismanaged implementation? The
right answer is almost certainly the most obvious one. During the first Tru=
mp administration, the <i>Post </i>thrived as a pillar of the resistance an=
d grew subscriptions by 50 percent year over year. But in the years since, =
it has suffered <i>severely</i>, losing nearly half its audience and as muc=
h as $100 million in annual revenue. Meanwhile, Bezos has spent years quiet=
ly and sometimes overtly signaling a desire to turn the <i>Post </i>into an=
 at least <i>semi</i>-nonpartisan news organization that services <i>all </=
i>Americans, rather than a regional edition of the <i>Times</i> political r=
eport servicing anxious liberals. Apparently, Bezos understands that Republ=
icans buy papers, too, and that advertisers also want to reach them. The <i=
>Post </i>may be an institution in town, but it=E2=80=99s also a business.<=
br/><br/>Now, despite <i>owning </i>the paper, there=E2=80=99s only so much=
 Bezos can actually do to manifest his vision for the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s=
 editorial posture
<i>without</i> actually putting his hands in the dough. The most obvious le=
ver is leadership. In 2022, Bezos hired <b>David Shipley</b> from centrist =
and billionaire-owned Bloomberg to oversee the editorial department, a move=
 he hoped would bring a greater diversity of perspective to its opinion pag=
es. Last year, he hired Lewis, a former <b>Murdoch </b>deputy and onetime D=
ow Jones C.E.O., to run the business and prioritize profitability over Puli=
tzers (notably, Lewis was in a bake-off with another Bloomberg-world vetera=
n, <b>Josh Steiner</b>). In both instances, Bezos hoped to burnish the <i>P=
ost</i>=E2=80=99s reputation for strong journalism while also moving the pa=
per away from its reputation as a liberal bulwark. Obviously, that has prov=
en harder than he might have hoped. <br/><br/>Anyway, Bezos seems to have f=
ound another outlet for his frustrations in the endorsement decision. Indee=
d, if you=E2=80=99re aspiring to create a nonpartisan newspaper=E2=80=94and=
 you=E2=80=99re a little displeased
with how that=E2=80=99s been going=E2=80=94it doesn=E2=80=99t really make s=
ense to compound reputational problems by once again telling people to vote=
 for the Democratic presidential candidate, which is exactly what the <i>Po=
st </i>has done since it began regularly endorsing candidates in 1976. Sure=
, even Bezos acknowledged that such a decision could and <i>should</i> have=
 been made earlier, before the final stretch of this fraught and emotionall=
y charged campaign, but such are the perils of being a titanic entrepreneur=
 and business magnate with so many irons in the fire, and so many private E=
uropean rail parties to attend.<br/><br/>Not surprisingly, the <i>vast </i>=
majority of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s own editorial board doesn=E2=80=99t s=
ee it that way, and has said as much publicly. In a meeting this week, audi=
o of which was obtained by The Washington Free Beacon, Shipley told his sta=
ff that he =E2=80=9Cmade very strenuous efforts, including a phone call [wi=
th Bezos] to change his mind, but failed.=E2=80=9D
Shipley=E2=80=99s decision to create some daylight between himself and both=
 Bezos and Lewis, who also wrote a mini-essay defending the non-endorsement=
 decision, was either bold, dastardly, defensive, or a manifestation of nak=
ed survival instincts. Never the most popular guy in the building, Shipley =
seemingly recognized that=E2=80=94in the short term, at least=E2=80=94the e=
leventh-hour non-endorsement decision was going to deliver a far more sever=
e reputational hit than one more cycle in which the never-Trumpers took sol=
ace in knowing the <i>Post </i>was firmly on their side. He also probably d=
idn=E2=80=99t want underlings to plot a coup against him, though Lewis coul=
dn=E2=80=99t be pleased that he broke rank.<br/><br/>In any event, there ar=
e at least two points that the critics of Bezos=E2=80=99s decision may not =
fully appreciate. First, despite their worst fears, there is <i>no </i>evid=
ence or indication that Bezos intends to tamper with the journalism itself.=
 Any sober review of the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s reporting
in recent days, weeks, or months would find <i>zero</i> deviation from its =
long-standing effort to hold Trump to account. (Of course, great reporting =
has the potential to have <i>far </i>greater impact on a presidential elect=
ion than any endorsement, which has exactly <i>no </i>bearing, but whatever=
=2E) The notion that Bezos intends to s=
hy away from tough journalism to placa=
te Trump is inconsistent with all the available evidence going back for nea=
rly a decade. <br/><br/>Second, while this whole thing was grossly mismanag=
ed, and has only compounded the newsroom=E2=80=99s preexisting obsession wi=
th finding its leadership guilty of philosophical adultery, it=E2=80=99s wo=
rth keeping in mind that the leaders have <i>their own</i> misgivings about=
 the newsroom, too. Ultimately, Bezos wants to own, and Lewis wants to mana=
ge, a paper staffed by a team that supports their vision for semi-nonpartis=
an, future-proofed profitability. And while they certainly don=E2=80=99t wa=
nt, and didn=E2=80=99t anticipate,
such a severe exodus of subscribers, they=E2=80=99re probably not terribly =
bothered by the departure of morally righteous journalists who pine for a r=
eturn to the =E2=80=9CDemocracy Dies in Darkness=E2=80=9D era, no matter wh=
at Marty posts on Twitter. As is the case in any business transformation, t=
hey may even welcome the turnover. <br/></td>
